PRETORIA The son of former SABC board member Hope Zinde will be re-admitted to Weskoppies Psychiatric Hospital in Pretoria for mental observation for a month.The North Gauteng High Court made the ruling on Thursday.Mark Zinde (23) is charged with murder, drug possession, assault, and attempted murder.He is accused of killing his 50-year-old mother in June last year.Hope Zinde was a well-known former journalist and television news anchor.Her body was found on June 11 last year in the boot of her car, outside her home in Pecanwood Estate at Hartbeespoort Dam in North West. Mark was initially referred for psychiatric evaluation following his arrest and Weskoppies declared him fit to stand trial. READ: Murder accused Mark Zinde hurls insults at judgeA hospital report stated that he did not suffer from any mental disorder when he allegedly killed his mother.Mark was released on R10,000 bail in September last year but was re-arrested in November, after allegedly attacking his father, Dr Lebohang Manoto, at his Walkerville home, south of Johannesburg.The State charged him with assault with the intention to cause grievous bodily harm, as well as attempted murder in connection with that case.Prosecutor Andr Wilsenach said Mark's re-admission was based on the assault and attempted murder charges.In December, the National Prosecuting Authority agreed to centralise the two cases.The defence and Mark's family have constantly insisted that he was not in his right mind when he allegedly killed his mother.The matter was postponed to August 29.African News Agency